<font color="#FF0000">MORE PROTESTOR WISDOM</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan 12 15:04:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Afterthought from a war protestor<br><br>
Just as soldiers worn uniforms, be they Air Force Blue or<br>
jungle green, so did the protestors.  We &quot;had&quot; to have our manditory long hair, braid and beads, stoned look, and obligatory peace sign on leather string.  Guess what comrades?  Hippy-pinko-long hairs got beaten up by god fearing christian american rednecks alot more often, and by gangs of drunk soldiers on leave, than soldiers in uniform got called baby killers or were spit on.  The silent majority, or what ever you want to cal Mom &amp; Pop Loyal American who set their kids off like sheep got real upset when confronted with that fact.  Their generation survived the &quot;big one&quot; (WW2) and the &quot;great depression&quot; (not their use of words: BIG one, GREAT depression), and they were conditioned to fight and die for that house in the suburbs and the steak dinner on Friday night.  How dare those dirty (I always showered, usually with their daughters) hippies come along and CHALLENGE their entire way of life?  That was the real undercurrent beneath the war protests.  That, and of course, cover thy own ass and stay out of the jungle.  Yes, many protestors were stoned scum, just as many as there were drunk red neck soldiers.  Nam sure proved one thing, that a young american with an automatic rifle in his hand is one mean killer.  What else did it accomplish?  Seems like the Viet's won, North and South. The North got the South, and most of the south came to the USA and have been living on our tax dollars since.  When America puts up a memorial to the protestors, to those who said my Country is wrong, then we will have matured and grown.<br><br>
the doc
